  "body": "<!-- Please use this template while reporting a bug and provide as much info as possible. Not doing so may result in your bug not being addressed in a timely manner. Thanks!\r\n\r\nIf the matter is security related, please disclose it privately via https://kubernetes.io/security/\r\n-->\r\n\r\n\r\n**What happened**:\r\n\r\nThe current implementation of NodeLifecycleController generates \"GET /api/v1/pods?fieldSelector=spec.nodeName=X\" request for each node becoming unavailable. This request can be expensive when there is a high number of pods (O(100k)) running in the cluster.\r\n\r\nThe problem is that to prepare answer for that request, kube-apiserver needs to fetch all the data from etcd and then filter out almost all of them (only ~100 pods can be running on a single nodes).\r\n\r\nIn scalability tests we are seeing that killing ~50 nodes in 5000 node cluster is able to overload master in a way that kube-controller-manager/kube-scheduler is not able to renew leader lock due to request timeout.\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blame/master/pkg/controller/util/node/controller_utils.go#L125\r\n\r\n**What you expected to happen**:\r\n\r\nI expected that killing 50 nodes in 5000 won't affect master's performance.\r\n\r\n**How to reproduce it (as minimally and precisely as possible)**:\r\n\r\n**Anything else we need to know?**:\r\n\r\nIn my opinion we should consider reimplementing this in some other way that will reduce master load.\r\n\r\nSome potential options:\r\n* Migrate to watch interface for pods (likely unfeasible due to freshness requirements)\r\n* Investigate what etcd offers for such requests\r\n* Implement some k8s-level index for spec.nodeName field (e.g. dedicated objects that for each node keeps a list of pods running on that node).\r\n\r\n**Environment**:\r\n- Kubernetes version (use `kubectl version`):\r\n- Cloud provider or hardware configuration:\r\n- OS (e.g: `cat /etc/os-release`):\r\n- Kernel (e.g. `uname -a`):\r\n- Install tools:\r\n- Network plugin and version (if this is a network-related bug):\r\n- Others:\r\n\r\n\r\n/cc @wojtek-t @krzysied \r\n/sig scalability",
